\begin{skill}{Ranger}{1.0}{ranger}
d3 5
a7 8
A few hardy souls, known as rangers, are trained to survive unequipped
in wilderness environments.  A ranger develops an instinctive sense of
direction.  They will become extremely sensitive to signs of
instrusion by humanoids, and so will become an expert at tracking and
recognising ambushes.  The ranger is knowledgable in herbalist lore,
which allows them to distinguish the properties of plants.  A ranger
will become comfortable with one particular environment, and will
operate best there.
d11 1
a11 95
\subsubsection{A Ranger can read a simple map if they can relate their
physical surroundings to the symbols on that map.}
\index{maps!reading}

Interpreting each new map is a challenge of the Ranger's wits and
experience. If a character does not have a map-reading skill, they may
not read maps.

A Ranger may place themselves on a map if they can determine the
direction of two marked landmarks.

\subsubsection{A ranger acquires a ``bump'' of direction as they
increase their Rank.}

A ranger instinctively knows the relationship of each of the cardinal
directions (of the compass) to each other.  They are able to pinpoint
true north to within (10 - Rank) degrees.  A ranger can also estimate
distance travelled overland to within (90 + Rank)\% accuracy.  The
maximum amount of travel which can be estimated by a ranger is (1 +
Rank) consecutive weeks' worth.  A check must be made to determine the
accuracy of the Ranger's estimate each time they reach their time
limit.  Both the above rules are exceptions to the maximum success
change of (90 + Rank)\% rule.

If a ranger is lost or wishes to travel out of a wilderland by a
direction other than that by which they came, their success percentage
to discover the shortest route out is (2 \x Perception + 7 \x Rank)\%.
The GM rolls percentile dice, and if the roll is equal to or less than
the success percentage, the ranger character chooses the quickest
route.  If the roll is between one and two times the success
percentage, the ranger is unsure of which direction to go, and may
check again in (12 - Rank) hours.  If the roll is equal to or greater
than twice the success percentage, the ranger has decided upon a
random direction as the best.

\subsubsection{A ranger can sometimes recognise an ambush in a natural
setting before they (or a fellow party member) blunders into it.}
\index{detect ambush!ranger}

A ranger has a (3 \x Perception + 5 \x Rank)\% chance to detect an
ambush or trap before they step into it.  Subtract 5\% per Rank of the
thief or ranger who set the trap or ambush from the success
percentage.

\subsubsection{A ranger can attempt to track the progress of land bound
beings through certain types of terrain.}

A ranger may only try to track somebody through terrain which will
show traces of passage.  For example, a human in armour can be tracked
through underbrush, but not across a mountain normally.

A ranger's success percentage to track, assuming that their quarry has
attempted to obscure signs of their passage, is (Perception + 6
\x Rank)\%.  The percentage is doubled if the quarry did not
attempt to cover their tracks; it is decreased by four times the Rank
of a ranger who used their craft in covering the tracks.  If the GM's
roll on percentile dice is equal to or less than the success
percentage, the ranger may track their quarry as far as the spoor
goes. If the roll is greater than the success percentage, the ranger
loses the trail an appreciable distance before they could run their
quarry to ground.

If a quarry's tracks can weather the passage of time, a ranger may
trace tracks of up to (2 + Rank Squared) days ago.

\subsubsection{A ranger can usually recognise the effect a particular
plant or animal product will have upon a humanoid.}

A ranger can always recognise a common animal or plant product (\eg
pine cones, deer meat).  When a ranger tries to determine the use of a
less common animal or plant product, their success percentage is equal
to (Perception + 10 \x Rank)\%.  If the GM's roll on percentile dice
is equal to or less than the success percentage, the ranger discovers
the properties of the substance under analysis.  If the roll is
between one and two times the success percentage, the ranger is unsure
of the substance's use.  If the roll is equal to or greater than twice
the success percentage, the ranger mistakenly identifies the substance
as something else which it could appear to be.

\subsubsection{A ranger can forage for curative plants in a woods
habitat.}

If a ranger spends a full day (about 12 hours) foraging in a woods
area, they may do one of the following:

\begin{Enumerate}
\item   Cure disease
\item   Cure fever
\item   Salve skin irritations
\item   Restore lost Endurance Points
\end{Enumerate}

The herbs gathered by the ranger will, when applied to a patient for
(12 - Rank) minutes, cure as if the ranger were a healer of same Rank
(see \S\ref{healer:cure}).
d13 140
a152 2
\subsubsection{A ranger can specialise in one particular environment.}
\label{ranger:speciality}
d154 1
a154 4
When a ranger achieves Rank 2, they may choose one of the environments
listed below as their speciality.  When a ranger performs an ability
in the environment of their speciality, they add (2 \x Rank)\% to
their success percentage.
d156 1
a156 1
A ranger may not specialise in more than one environment.
d158 34
a191 3
\subsubsection{A ranger may increase the chance of a favourable
reaction when encountering an animal in the environment of their
speciality.}
d193 2
a194 3
The reaction dice roll is increased by two for every Rank the ranger
has achieved.  The ranger forfeits this bonus if they (or any
accompanying party member) take hostile action towards the beast.
d196 2
a197 2
\subsection{Ranger Environment List}
\label{tables!environments}
d199 4
a202 1
\index{tables!environments}
d205 5
d211 22
a232 11
Includes all caves, tunnels, natural caverns, and other underground
areas which are not part of an inhabited dwelling.
\item[Crypts]
Includes all barrows, crypts, burial mounds, graveyards, and other
places of interment for the dead.
\item[Fields]
Includes cultivated fields, vineyards, moors, heaths, etc (usually
near inhabited areas).
\item[Marshes]
Includes swamps, meres, ponds, etc.  In addition, small streams and
rivers are included herein.
d234 12
a245 7
Includes all plains, steppes, and other more or less open and flat or
rolling terrain.
\item[Rough]
Includes both hills and mountains.
\item[Ruins]
Includes all abandoned dwellings (cities, castles, monasteries,
villages, etc).
d247 11
a257 2
Includes all deserts, wastelands, salt flats, where life is not
likely to be found in profusion.
d259 4
a262 2
All wooded glens, forests, brush land, etc., where large amounts of
common wildlife are likely to be found and where few humanoids dwell.
